     1вҶ’# Archived project. No maintenance. 
     3вҶ’This project is not maintained anymore and is archived. Feel free to fork and
     4вҶ’make your own changes if needed. For more detail read my blog post: [Taking an indefinite sabbatical from my projects](https://arslan.io/2018/10/09/taking-an-indefinite-sabbatical-from-my-projects/)
     5вҶ’
     6вҶ’Thanks to everyone for their valuable feedback and contributions.
     7вҶ’
     8вҶ’# Structs [![GoDoc](http://img.shields.io/badge/go-documentation-blue.svg?style=flat-square)](http://godoc.org/github.com/fatih/structs) [![Build Status](http://img.shields.io/travis/fatih/structs.svg?style=flat-square)](https://travis-ci.org/fatih/structs) [![Coverage Status](http://img.shields.io/coveralls/fatih/structs.svg?style=flat-square)](https://coveralls.io/r/fatih/structs)
    10вҶ’Structs contains various utilities to work with Go (Golang) structs. It was
    11вҶ’initially used by me to convert a struct into a `map[string]interface{}`. With
    12вҶ’time I've added other utilities for structs.  It's basically a high level
    13вҶ’package based on primitives from the reflect package. Feel free to add new
    14вҶ’functions or improve the existing code.
    15вҶ’
    16вҶ’## Install
    18вҶ’```bash
    19вҶ’go get github.com/fatih/structs
    20вҶ’```
    21вҶ’
    22вҶ’## Usage and Examples
    24вҶ’Just like the standard lib `strings`, `bytes` and co packages, `structs` has
    25вҶ’many global functions to manipulate or organize your struct data. Lets define
    26вҶ’and declare a struct:
    27вҶ’
    28вҶ’```go
    29вҶ’type Server struct {
    30вҶ’	Name        string `json:"name,omitempty"`
    31вҶ’	ID          int
    32вҶ’	Enabled     bool
    33вҶ’	users       []string // not exported
    34вҶ’	http.Server          // embedded
    35вҶ’}
    36вҶ’
    37вҶ’server := &Server{
    38вҶ’	Name:    "gopher",
    39вҶ’	ID:      123456,
    40вҶ’	Enabled: true,
    41вҶ’}
    42вҶ’```
    43вҶ’
    44вҶ’```go
    45вҶ’// Convert a struct to a map[string]interface{}
    46вҶ’// => {"Name":"gopher", "ID":123456, "Enabled":true}
    47вҶ’m := structs.Map(server)
    48вҶ’
    49вҶ’// Convert the values of a struct to a []interface{}
    50вҶ’// => ["gopher", 123456, true]
    51вҶ’v := structs.Values(server)
    52вҶ’
    53вҶ’// Convert the names of a struct to a []string
    54вҶ’// (see "Names methods" for more info about fields)
    55вҶ’n := structs.Names(server)
    56вҶ’
    57вҶ’// Convert the values of a struct to a []*Field
    58вҶ’// (see "Field methods" for more info about fields)
    59вҶ’f := structs.Fields(server)
    60вҶ’
    61вҶ’// Return the struct name => "Server"
    62вҶ’n := structs.Name(server)
    63вҶ’
    64вҶ’// Check if any field of a struct is initialized or not.
    65вҶ’h := structs.HasZero(server)
    66вҶ’
    67вҶ’// Check if all fields of a struct is initialized or not.
    68вҶ’z := structs.IsZero(server)
    69вҶ’
    70вҶ’// Check if server is a struct or a pointer to struct
    71вҶ’i := structs.IsStruct(server)
    72вҶ’```
    73вҶ’
    74вҶ’### Struct methods
    76вҶ’The structs functions can be also used as independent methods by creating a new
    77вҶ’`*structs.Struct`. This is handy if you want to have more control over the
    78вҶ’structs (such as retrieving a single Field).
    79вҶ’
    80вҶ’```go
    81вҶ’// Create a new struct type:
    82вҶ’s := structs.New(server)
    83вҶ’
    84вҶ’m := s.Map()              // Get a map[string]interface{}
    85вҶ’v := s.Values()           // Get a []interface{}
    86вҶ’f := s.Fields()           // Get a []*Field
    87вҶ’n := s.Names()            // Get a []string
    88вҶ’f := s.Field(name)        // Get a *Field based on the given field name
    89вҶ’f, ok := s.FieldOk(name)  // Get a *Field based on the given field name
    90вҶ’n := s.Name()             // Get the struct name
    91вҶ’h := s.HasZero()          // Check if any field is uninitialized
    92вҶ’z := s.IsZero()           // Check if all fields are uninitialized
    93вҶ’```
    94вҶ’
    95вҶ’### Field methods
    97вҶ’We can easily examine a single Field for more detail. Below you can see how we
    98вҶ’get and interact with various field methods:
    99вҶ’
   100вҶ’
   101вҶ’```go
   102вҶ’s := structs.New(server)
   103вҶ’
   104вҶ’// Get the Field struct for the "Name" field
   105вҶ’name := s.Field("Name")
   106вҶ’
   107вҶ’// Get the underlying value,  value => "gopher"
   108вҶ’value := name.Value().(string)
   109вҶ’
   110вҶ’// Set the field's value
   111вҶ’name.Set("another gopher")
   112вҶ’
   113вҶ’// Get the field's kind, kind =>  "string"
   114вҶ’name.Kind()
   115вҶ’
   116вҶ’// Check if the field is exported or not
   117вҶ’if name.IsExported() {
   118вҶ’	fmt.Println("Name field is exported")
   119вҶ’}
   120вҶ’
   121вҶ’// Check if the value is a zero value, such as "" for string, 0 for int
   122вҶ’if !name.IsZero() {
   123вҶ’	fmt.Println("Name is initialized")
   124вҶ’}
   125вҶ’
   126вҶ’// Check if the field is an anonymous (embedded) field
   127вҶ’if !name.IsEmbedded() {
   128вҶ’	fmt.Println("Name is not an embedded field")
   129вҶ’}
   130вҶ’
   131вҶ’// Get the Field's tag value for tag name "json", tag value => "name,omitempty"
   132вҶ’tagValue := name.Tag("json")
   133вҶ’```
   134вҶ’
   135вҶ’Nested structs are supported too:
   136вҶ’
   137вҶ’```go
   138вҶ’addrField := s.Field("Server").Field("Addr")
   139вҶ’
   140вҶ’// Get the value for addr
   141вҶ’a := addrField.Value().(string)
   142вҶ’
   143вҶ’// Or get all fields
   144вҶ’httpServer := s.Field("Server").Fields()
   145вҶ’```
   146вҶ’
   147вҶ’We can also get a slice of Fields from the Struct type to iterate over all
   148вҶ’fields. This is handy if you wish to examine all fields:
   149вҶ’
   150вҶ’```go
   151вҶ’s := structs.New(server)
   152вҶ’
   153вҶ’for _, f := range s.Fields() {
   154вҶ’	fmt.Printf("field name: %+v\n", f.Name())
   155вҶ’
   156вҶ’	if f.IsExported() {
   157вҶ’		fmt.Printf("value   : %+v\n", f.Value())
   158вҶ’		fmt.Printf("is zero : %+v\n", f.IsZero())
   159вҶ’	}
   160вҶ’}
   161вҶ’```
   162вҶ’
